                            "id": "H_excess_curve_interior",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "H_excess vs T_i_n (interior, zero fluxes): straight line through (T_f, 0) with slope c_i*Δz_i/Δt — energy deficit for cold layers, energy surplus for warm layers.",
                            "x": { "variable": "T_i_n", "label": "T_i_n (K)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "H_excess", "label": "H_excess (W/m^2)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "H_excess_vs_T_i_n_top",
                    "description": "Top variant: same temperature sweep as the interior example but with is_top = 1.0 and a representative surface forcing h_n = 100 W/m^2 with dh_dT = -10 W/(m^2*K). The top variant adds h_n + dh_dT*(T_f - T_i_n) to the layer's energy balance — when the layer is cold (T_i_n < T_f), the linearization slope amplifies the surface flux (negative dh_dT × positive (T_f - T_i_n) > 0 → enhanced flux into the layer when cold); when the layer is warm, the flux is reduced. Compared to the interior example, the curve is shifted upward by the surface-forcing contribution and tilted by the dh_dT slope.",
